,"value":"goloroden"},"title":{"matchLevel":"none","matchedWords":[],"value":"A SQL-Inspired Query Language Designed for Event Sourcing (2025)"},"url":{"matchLevel":"none","matchedWords":[],"value":"https://yoeight.github.io/blog/2025/12/21/EventQL_A_SQL_Inspired_Query_Language_Designed_For_Event_Sourcing.html"}},"_tags":["story","author_goloroden","story_48126014","front_page"],"author":"goloroden","children":[48155228],"created_at":"2026-05-13T19:02:52Z","created_at_i":1778698972,"num_comments":0,"objectID":"48126014","points":10,"story_id":48126014,"title":"A SQL-Inspired Query Language Designed for Event Sourcing (2025)","updated_at":"2026-05-16T00:12:45Z","url":"https://yoeight.github.io/blog/2025/12/21/EventQL_A_SQL_Inspired_Query_Language_Designed_For_Event_Sourcing.html"},{"_highlightResult":{"author":{"matchLevel":"none","matchedWords":[],"value":"dimastopel"},"story_text":{"matchLevel":"none","matchedWords":[],"value":"Back in 2012 I built <a href=\"https://cert-depot.com\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://cert-depot.com</a> as a weekend project. Node.js + Express + jQuery, shelling out to OpenSSL for certificate generation. It worked but I eventually let it rot. <a href=\"https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=4766743\">https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=4766743</a><p>Rewrote it from scratch in Go. The entire thing is a single binary with no external dependencies:<p>1. Certificate generation uses Go's crypto/x509 (no OpenSSL)<p>2. Certificates are generated in memory and streamed directly \u2014 nothing is stored on the server<p>3. RSA 2048/4096 and ECDSA P-256/P-384<p>4. Subject Alternative Names (required by browsers since Chrome 58)<p>5. ZIP (PEM files) or PFX/PKCS#12 output<p>You comments / suggestions / bug reports are very welcome. Thanks.<p>Source: <a href=\"https://github.com/dimastopel/certdepot\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://github.com/dimastopel/certdepot</a>"},"title":{"matchLevel":"none","matchedWords":[],"value":"Show HN: I rewrote my 2012 self-signed cert generator in Go \u2013 cert-depot.com"}},"_tags":["story","author_dimastopel","story_47613622","show_hn","front_page"],"author":"dimastopel","children":[47618945],"created_at":"2026-04-02T12:36:10Z","created_at_i":1775133370,"num_comments":1,"objectID":"47613622","points":9,"story_id":47613622,"story_text":"Back in 2012 I built <a href=\"https:&#x2F;&#x2F;cert-depot.com\" rel=\"nofollow\">https:&#x2F;&#x2F;cert-depot.com</a> as a weekend project. Node.js + Express + jQuery, shelling out to OpenSSL for certificate generation. It worked but I eventually let it rot. <a href=\"https:&#x2F;&#x2F;news.ycombinator.com&#x2F;item?id=4766743\">https:&#x2F;&#x2F;news.ycombinator.com&#x2F;item?id=4766743</a><p>Rewrote it from scratch in Go. The entire thing is a single binary with no external dependencies:<p>1. Certificate generation uses Go&#x27;s crypto&#x2F;x509 (no OpenSSL)<p>2. Certificates are generated in memory and streamed directly \u2014 nothing is stored on the server<p>3. RSA 2048&#x2F;4096 and ECDSA P-256&#x2F;P-384<p>4. Subject Alternative Names (required by browsers since Chrome 58)<p>5. ZIP (PEM files) or PFX&#x2F;PKCS#12 output<p>You comments &#x2F; suggestions &#x2F; bug reports are very welcome. Thanks.<p>Source: <a href=\"https:&#x2F;&#x2F;github.com&#x2F;dimastopel&#x2F;certdepot\" rel=\"nofollow\">https:&#x2F;&#x2F;github.com&#x2F;dimastopel&#x2F;certdepot</a>","title":"Show HN: I rewrote my 2012 self-signed cert generator in Go \u2013 cert-depot.com","updated_at":"2026-04-06T06:43:48Z"},{"_highlightResult":{"author":{"matchLevel":"none","matchedWords":[],"value":"lizmat"},"title":{"matchLevel":"none","matchedWords":[],"value":"Making your JITted Code known: Let me count the ways"},"url":{"matchLevel":"none","matchedWords":[],"value":"https://wakelift.de/2026/03/09/making-your-jitted-code-known-let-me-count-the-ways/"}},"_tags":["story","author_lizmat","story_47320921","front_page"],"author":"lizmat","children":[47383626],"created_at":"2026-03-10T09:31:19Z","created_at_i":1773135079,"num_comments":1,"objectID":"47320921","points":9,"story_id":47320921,"title":"Making your JITted Code known: Let me count the ways","updated_at":"2026-03-15T02:25:00Z","url":"https://wakelift.de/2026/03/09/making-your-jitted-code-known-let-me-count-the-ways/"},{"_highlightResult":{"author":{"matchLevel":"none","matchedWords":[],"value":"ibobev"},"title":{"matchLevel":"none","matchedWords":[],"value":"When Coupled Volcanoes Talk, These Researchers Listen"},"url":{"matchLevel":"none","matchedWords":[],"value":"https://www.quantamagazine.org/when-coupled-volcanoes-talk-these-researchers-listen-20260327/"}},"_tags":["story","author_ibobev","story_47544114","front_page"],"author":"ibobev","created_at":"2026-03-27T15:40:23Z","created_at_i":1774626023,"num_comments":0,"objectID":"47544114","points":9,"story_id":47544114,"title":"When Coupled Volcanoes Talk, These Researchers Listen","updated_at":"2026-03-30T11:28:05Z","url":"https://www.quantamagazine.org/when-coupled-volcanoes-talk-these-researchers-listen-20260327/"},{"_highlightResult":{"author":{"matchLevel":"none","matchedWords":[],"value":"tomjakubowski"},"title":{"matchLevel":"none","matchedWords":[],"value":"The main thing about P2P meth is that there's so much of it (2022)"},"url":{"matchLevel":"none","matchedWords":[],"value":"https://dynomight.net/p2p-meth/"}},"_tags":["story","author_tomjakubowski","story_48155324","front_page"],"author":"tomjakubowski","created_at":"2026-05-15T23:37:32Z","created_at_i":1778888252,"num_comments":0,"objectID":"48155324","points":6,"story_id":48155324,"title":"The main thing about P2P meth is that there's so much of it (2022)","updated_at":"2026-05-16T00:12:15Z","url":"https://dynomight.net/p2p-meth/"},{"_highlightResult":{"author":{"matchLevel":"none","matchedWords":[],"value":"robohobo"},"title":{"matchLevel":"none","matchedWords":[],"value":"SnapState - Persistent state for AI agent workflows"},"url":{"matchLevel":"none","matchedWords":[],"valu